":1,"options":["Left second intercostal space","Right fourth intercostal space","Left fifth intercostal space","Right second intercostal space","Left fourth intercostal space"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe aortic valve is best auscultated at the \u003Cstrong\u003Eright second intercostal space\u003C/strong\u003E, adjacent to the sternum. This location allows for optimal listening to the sounds produced by the aortic valve during the cardiac cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther auscultation sites for heart valves include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft second intercostal space\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used for the pulmonary valve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eright fourth intercostal space\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard auscultation site for any valve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft fifth intercostal space\u003C/strong\u003E (apex) is used for the mitral valve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft fourth intercostal space\u003C/strong\u003E (lower left sternal border) is used for the tricuspid valve\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these specific auscultation sites is crucial for accurate cardiac examination and assessment of valve function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The aortic valve is best auscultated at the right second intercostal space, adjacent to the sternum.","Each heart valve has a specific auscultation site on the chest wall for optimal sound detection."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Talley, N. J., \u0026 O\u0027connor, S. (2014). Clinical examination: a systematic guide to physical diagnosis. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47045"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions",